  "summary": "Muto and Mutsuji travel through a desolate, wintry landscape toward the Inari Shrine, passing through the northern Kyoto Basin near Mount Danwa. They drive through the territory of the Matsuzaki family, characterized by a half-collapsed, elliptical iron gate and a neglected, tree-lined avenue. Their destination is Inkyou Castle, also known as Sparrow Castle, a Gothic-style mansion with blue conical roofs and three spires. Mutsuji explains that the castle's name derives from a prose poem by Luigi Righetto, in which a sparrow personifies death coming for children at dawn; he notes that Righetto was himself executed for murdering women.\n\nUpon arrival, the pair observes several Kyoto Prefectural Police vehicles, including a gray forensic department car, parked by a fountain. Mutsuji concludes that a murder case has likely occurred. As they approach the mansion, they are greeted by Detective Tsubaki, a straightforward man in a trench coat who has previously helped Mutsu thrive within the police force. The group prepares to meet with a man named Mr. Itou.",
